commentText: ok!!!! so, i am sitting here letting my OWN nails dry as you're coming out of the salon and as i'm letting it dry i can't really do much else except watch your video (as opposed to being able to do my nails and "listen" to you) but anyway, i'm watching you drive and talk and i just had an idea! you're in the car and i'm really getting a good look at your "source of contention for so many, your elusive eyebrows" and i think...if you were to just maybe do a light pencil at the beginning of your brow (near the bridge of your nose) just some light strokes there to meet with your real brows (not even really going into your real brows except where the two would meet. i think that would look beautiful!!! you have such nice natural brows that you really only need to add a few at the beginning to make them a tad longer! i think this would put the bed the whole ordeal and on days you feel like shuzzing them up it would take you no time at all! just an idea of course and i know your sick of the whole thing and if you don't really want to do the whole microblading thing i think this might just work and be an easy fix! i love when you don't even wear anything so i get pissed that you feel so compelled to do them out of so many people telling you that you need to. i love you with, without, bare faced, make-up faced, all encompassing kandy. just had an epiphany and wanted to stop the video and share. have a blast in california, you're probably asleep on friday at the hotel as i type this =) can't wait to hear how it went!

commentText: There's something potentially misleading about a statement like "75% of the new jobs are in [insert any state here]." It's not good to use percentage numbers when the numbers could be negative. To illustrate the problem, imagine a 3-state country. Suppose two of the states each add 7500 jobs apiece in a given month, while the third state loses 5000 jobs. That's 15000 jobs added, and 5000 jobs lost, for a net gain of 10000 jobs. So the first two states can both claim "75% of the job growth in the country comes from our state." And they're both correct...sort of...

commentText: Every state has its own (often geographically driven) issues.  In CA, homelessness is a good example.  It isn't quite the mess conservative sites make it out to be, and it certainly is not stoked by 'liberal' policies or anything like that... but it's still a major problem.  Certainly a bigger problem than we'd see in states where the weather conspires to force shelter.   But that doesn't mean other states have less of a problem... states like Mississippi don't actually count homeless as homeless.  'Poverty and Homelessness' in one state is not equivalent to 'Poverty and Homelessness' in another, simply by virtue of how state governments count those people.  In California's case the homeless are pushed into the limelight by the insane housing market.  Rents and home prices have gone through the roof due to demand and the continuous, huge, cash influx into the state from the (international) tech industry.  Weather is mild year-round, so there is little cyclical pressure on the homeless to have to find actual shelter beyond a tent.  They wind up, very visible, in tent communities under highway overpasses, along the borders of industrial areas, and other places.  The entire west coast of the U.S. is like this.  The tech industry isn't just Silicon Valley.... tech is attracted to the West Coast of the U.S. (of which CA is a big piece) by the presence of a highly-educated, technically-savvy workforce that numbers in the millions.  It overflows S.V., it overflows San Francisco, it overflows all the nearby cities including the ones that used to be crime-ridden like Oakland and Richmond (which have become much less so over the last decade, though its still pretty bad in certain areas).   The same thing is happening in the greater L.A. area.  In Seattle, in Vancouver (Canada), etc.  Gentrification runs rampant because of this overflow situation and the need for all those workers to find housing, spreading out from mass-transit hubs.  You can get from Berkeley to SF (all the way across the bay) in 20 minutes on BART, for example.  Gentrification (primarily realized by the insane rental and housing markets) is the primary driver behind people leaving the state.  In other-words, CA is 'full' (at least when it comes to housing anywhere along the coasts).  It's not taxes, liberal politics, or anything else.  Its simple housing pressure.  -Matt
